WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:19.000
The Root 303 corridor is a heavily traveled arterial that passes through the heart of the

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:23.000
communities of Tapan, Orangeburg, and Blauville.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:27.000
In order to enhance traffic safety and improve the quality of life for residents and businesses

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.000
along the roadway.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
The town of Orangetown, the Rockland County Planning Department, the New York Metropolitan

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Transportation Council, and the New York State DOT, have jointly undertaken the Root 303

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Sustainable Development Study.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Assisted by Wilbur Smith Associates, the study consulted.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:50.000
These agencies conducted a series of open public forum meetings called SHARETS, where

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.000
community members were invited to discuss their concerns, suggestions, and visions for

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:56.000
the Root 303 corridor.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:05.000
We're concerned about the future of the community, the land uses in the corridor, and how

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.000
this corridor fits into the town, into the county, and into the region.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.000
So yes, it's transportation, but it's so much more than that.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:20.000
We have a true opportunity to do something here that's exemplary, that we can do something

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:28.000
about transportation, and really make an example of how we can be forward thinking.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
It would be a wonderful thing.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.000
A SHARETS is a name that we've given to an approach, which really tries to lay out in

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
a series of meetings and number of issues, and let people work constructively through

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:43.000
those issues.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
Three SHARETS have been scheduled during the study period.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
At the first SHARET, eight topics were brought up for discussion, dealing with issues pertaining

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.000
to the Root 303 corridor and surrounding areas.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
This involved in the study explained the issues associated with each topic and facilitated

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
discussions among the participants.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
We have to be able to maintain access in the areas so that the businesses can survive.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:10.000
They're crazy.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
They just know close to the red light, noticing.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:19.000
Now I want a left hand turn, all 303, and a very strange.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Let's try to make 303 a nice road.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
It is a nice road.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Let's make it safe.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Let's clean it up.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:32.000
If this was eliminated here, and then from here and here, there was like a left only.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
I'm really interested to know kind of where you live in the corridor.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:39.000
We're also you guys think that we could put some landscaping in.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Following the first SHARET, a study team discussed the feedback called from the breakout groups

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:51.000
and created three clear-cut scenarios or alternatives on how the 303 corridor could be redeveloped,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
concentrating on town centers, open space, and business emphasis.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:02.000
It's difficult for a community to come together and describe a future vision in a consensual

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
way, and these workshops are intended to try to bring you through that out, so we can

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.000
begin to start modeling alternatives.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
The first topic discussed was town centers.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.000
I'm looking at this corridor now as the next 100 years.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
I'm not looking anymore at today.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:27.000
I'm looking to see what I would like to live in 100 years from now, and I want a village.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
I would vision maybe some small village centers where they're easily accessible by foot, where

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
people can travel down 303 at a comfortable pace, pull into an area, park, and spend some

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.000
time in an area without having to worry about getting in their car and going to the next

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:44.000
big parking lot.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.000
The second scenario, open space.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
I think we should remember open space preservation.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
I think that maybe we could be looking to our local officials to be putting in incentives

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:02.000
for donating land for the purpose of open space.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:07.000
The third and final scenario, business emphasis.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
I think the purpose of this meeting is to make the kind of transportation corridor and

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:18.000
kind of zoning, the kind of planning that will attract the kinds of business that is

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
essential for maintaining a good form of life in this town.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
These big box establishments are literally sucking the life out of a local economy.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
And if the businesses could be located close enough to these little centers, maybe somebody

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
would take a ten minute walk on their lunch break.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
There has to be some limitation put on what can be built where and how much of it can

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:45.000
be built and it's basically a negotiation.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Following the second charret, the study team analyzed the feedback obtained during the

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:50.000
three sessions.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Here at Eerie Street, right now they've shown us with these bump hounds and everybody

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.000
liked that when we went to the meeting.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:04.000
What they'd also like to do is to do that textured pavement so we need to show that on this

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:05.000
photo.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Ultimately, the final plan submitted at the third charret would incorporate aspects of each

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
of the three land-use scenarios.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Fundamentally, what we want to try to do is to say, look at this is how we're interpreting

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:18.000
all this input.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
These are the scenarios.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
This is what we're going to take to detail testing.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Do you have any final take on it?

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:32.000
If we've done our job correctly, what we'll end up with is a set of an approach that gives

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:39.000
us a better solution that either of the solutions individually result that in essence kind

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:44.000
of optimizes the corridor will bring that result back to the community and say, hey,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:51.000
this looks like the combination of what you've said, it looks like our result of an analysis.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:52.000
What do you think?

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And then we'll make some final adjustments and if the process comes out like I think it

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
will, I think we'll come up with a vision.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
The goal is to put all of that together into a plan and then to allow the town board to

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
implement those suggestions in terms of zone changes and traffic safety improvements.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:14.000
For further information, we invite you to contact the Route 303 Sustainable Development Study

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:14.000
team.

